What an amazing opportunity. Across the world and back in less than 5 days.  Los Angeles to Latvia took about 25 hours each way, but it was worth it to perform for the amazing men and women of the Canadian armed forces, as well as the NATO forces. It was a privilege meeting so many people who put their lives on the line for all of us and to be a part of such a rocking show to show our appreciation. Thanks Mick, Brent, Marc, and Shaun @sv_trislide for letting me feel like part of the band. #keeponrockininthefreeworld 🇨🇦. Also huge shout out to @skip_lx and @emwmusik for making us all look and sound amazing!

I was a deeply troubled 15 year old kid when I stumbled into Loose Moose Theatre for the first time. Like most of the best things in life it was a through chance I went. A beautiful accident. I didn’t know I was stepping into a bit of magic. Pushing through the wardrobe and coats into a land of like minded bandits learning about improvisation. It was the chocolate factory, and from that day forward I spent every single weekend at that theatre with my friend John learning about improv, and comedy, and theatre with the other Oompa Loompa. 

Our Willy Wonka was Keith. Keith would trundle into the theatre in his giant parka and boots looking like an arctic explorer who accidentally stumbled into a theatre class on his way to ice fish. His welcoming English accent made him seem a mad professor created from a Roald Dahl book. We’d try our hardest to impress him and the audiences, only to have him call out seemingly counter intuitive advice to us. 

“You’re trying too hard” “Be Average”
“Don’t be prepared”
“Failure is important. If every scene was perfect the show would be terrible!”
“Stop stalling and let him eat you!”

He taught us to run towards fire.
“In real life we don’t want you to answer the door to an axe murderer, but that would make for very boring theatre.”

Hearing him laugh from the side of the stage was hypnotic, and just as likely to occur when you said something brilliant, as when you said something disastrous. 

He taught me that there was magic on stage. How to play and find joy in failing. He bonded me to other ragtag misfits forming the strongest friendships of my life. 

He showed my I wasn’t alone, and that through improv and performing I could forge connections with people I never would think to in day to day life. Where else would a 37 year old accountant perform a bank robbery with a 19 year old exchange student? Or a 15 year old boy with razor marks on his arm go on a hot air balloon ride with a 60 year widow. 

The world he showed us was magic. He was magic. I can see him in that giant parka now. Shrugging it off like a chrysalis. Opening his wings and fluttering off to the next bright light out there. 

Good bye Keith. 

What comes next?

What can I say. Tonight is the series finale of @workinmoms in Canada on @cbc. I never expected the 7 year rocket ship I’d be on when @reitcatou asked me to join the cast of this show. I loved the cast and crew so much, but for me it was all about this lady here. My buddy @danikindofficial. Her incredible skills as an actor are only matched by her depth of personal character. To have her in your corner is to have an ally for life. 99% of my scenes were with her. She made me look good every step of the way, and kept me laughing between takes. Anne and Lionel forever ❤️. Can’t wait for you all to see in @netflix next month.  Thanks to @ystaav for this awesome candid post wrap picture.

Sometimes it can be easier to focus on when someone we love leaves our life, but I prefer to think about when they come into it. 10 years ago. It was a lifetime ago but today I’m brought back to it like it was yesterday. 

A decade has past since this amazing little girl came into ours like a tornado. We had less than a month with her, but she changed us forever. It’s hard not to sink into sadness at painful memories. Memories that are duller with time, but still have jagged edges you find yourself catching on when you roll them in your hands. Doctors explaining #trisomy18 to us, saying cold clinical terms like “incompatible with life”. It’s difficult not to feel the heat of that familiar anger in my chest at a cruel and unfair universe. One that would deal such an unfair hand to this little girl. 

But in less than a month you changed our lives.  Made me a better man. Taught me  to fight against impossible odds. Taught me that when I’m falling, those I love when hold me and help soften the impact. Taught me that I, like so many of us, was naive to think the universe was fair, but that’s ok. The beauty of life is that it is a heartbreaking bargain. The ante at the table is high, but the game is worth it. With joy comes pain, and pain comes joy. 

Mostly I’ve learned to try and hold tightly to the beautiful moments we do get, and not focus on the painful. 
 
So, today I think about a beautiful little girl with hiccups, snuggling on her daddy’s chest. Happy Birthday MJB
